                               ATTENTION!!!
       IT IS ALWAYS A GOOD IDEA TO MAKE A COPY OF THE ORIGINAL DISKETTE
                 AND USE ONLY THE COPY IN DAY TO DAY WORK.

To install ADinf in your machine, insert the diskette containing
the ADinf program into drive A (or B whichever is appropriate to
your system), log on to the ADINF directory with the commands

> a: (or b:) and press Enter

> cd: \adinf and press Enter

and type

> install

and press Enter, and answer all the questions of the setup program.

Depending on whether this is the first time your are installing  in  your
system or whether you are upgrading an earlier version, the Setup program
behaves differently.

   IF THIS IS THE FIRST TIME YOU ARE INSTALLING ADINF IN YOUR MACHINE:
on pressing <Enter> after typing the installation command line, you will
be prompted to

  ┌──────── Type a directory for installing ADinf ─────────╖
  │  C:\ADINF_                                             ║██
  ╘════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝██
    ██████████████████████████████████████████████████████████

If you accept the directory proposed by the Setup program, press <Enter>.
Or, type a different pathname and press <Enter>. If you yourself have not
created a directory for installing ADinf, on pressing <Enter>,  the Setup
will respond as follows:

  ┌────────────────────────── ! ───────────────────────────╖
  │                 Directory not found!                   ║██
  │                                                        ║██
  │                      C:\ADinf                          ║██
  │    CREATE                              DON'T CREATE    ║██
  ╘════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝██
    ██████████████████████████████████████████████████████████

Press <Enter> to create a directory.  Then the Setup creates a directory
and after copying the files to it, displays a query:

  ┌───────────────────────── ?! ───────────────────────────╖
  │                                                        ║██
  │           Add ADinf to AUTOEXEC.BAT file ?             ║██
  │                                                        ║██
  │      ADD                                DON'T ADD      ║██
  ╘════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝██
    ██████████████████████████████████████████████████████████

If you want to tack ADinf  to your AUTOEXEC.BAT file, press <Enter>;  else
choose DON'T  ADD.  If you  choose ADD,  on pressing  <Enter>, you will be
prompted to mark the drives you want to put under check by ADinf:

     ┌───────────────────────╖
     │    C  D  E  F  G  H   ║██
     │    ^                  ║██
     ╘═══════════════════════╝██
       █████████████████████████

Moving the up arrowhead cursor with <Right>, <Left> or <Tab> keys from one
letter to another, mark the drives with the <Space> or <Ins> key for which
you want to create diskinfo tables. Press <Enter> to finish your selection.

Then the screen will show your  AUTOEXEC.BAT file, typing each entry in  a
separate line.  Using the <Up>  or  <Down> keys, move the selection bar to
the place where you want to tack the ADinf command line to the AUTOEXEC.BAT
file and press <Enter>.  Your old  AUTOEXEC.BAT  file will be  renamed  to
AUTOEXEC.ADI.  If you do not want to modify the  AUTOEXEC.BAT  file, press
the <Esc> key.  Then the Setup program will respond as follows:

  ┌──────────────────────── ?! ────────────────────────────╖
  │                                                        ║██
  │                 Create ADinf tables ?                  ║██
  │                                                        ║██
  │       CREATE                          DON'T CREATE     ║██
  ╘════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝██
    ██████████████████████████████████████████████████████████

If you answer  CREATE, then before building up diskinfo  tables, the Setup
program  prompts  you  to  change  the  default  name  of  the  table file
Adinf═☼═.░░░.   The point is that in future  viruses  may be  specifically
designed to dodge  detection  by  ADinf.  Today there is already  a virus,
which  tries  to  delete  the  files  whose  names  begin  with the letter
combination  ADIN.   For  this  reason  the  Setup  program invites you to
rename the diskinfo  tables file.   You can change  to any name  you like,
the main idea is to goof such  viruses.  Regardless of whether or not  you
rename the file, press <Enter> to finish installation.


  IF YOU ARE UPGRADING AN OLDER VERSION ALREADY INSTALLED IN YOUR MACHINE,
the installation procedure is the same as described above, but  the  Setup
program will ask your permission to overwrite the old ADinf version in the
system. It will not prompt you to tack ADinf to your AUTOEXEC.BAT file nor
will it create diskinfo tables afresh because later versions recognize and
use the tables created by earlier versions.
